There are 3 types of error as
  a. Compile time errors : Error shown will compilation (Syntax wale)
  b. Runtime Errors :  Execution stops due to them, these are clas Exeption
  c. Logical Error :  No syntastical -> they are Bugs in code

 Even though the runtime error exists, the application should not be stopped at all, so we handle the error;
 this is clas exception handling.


 For handling them we use tryCatch block. Shown In file

 use Customised Message for specific type of errors like catching them , We can have multiple catch block for a single try.

 try{}
 catch(ArithmeticExeption e ){
    sout("Aukat me Udo");
 }
 catch(ArrayIndexOutOfBoundException e){
    sout("Hero Bnn Rha Hai Ky");
}
catch(Exception e){
    sout("Something went wrong")
}

But we will need many exception catching block for just error so also give one catch block(Exception e) for handling all exception (kyuki ek ek bhi kbb tkk dedege)

Parent exception [Exception e] should always be at tip


The Parent Exception class also extends the class -> Throwable;
class Throwable is implemented by two Classes as Error and Exception

Exception -> 2 main types
Unchecked Exception  : the Compiler when dont force to handle the exception, its totally upon us to handle or not

Checked exception : We reaaly need to handle them

Runtime exception are unchecked exception and rest of the exception like SQL exception IO exception are the checked exception
there r multiple types of runtime exception as Nullptr exception, ArithmeticException , ArrayIndexOutOfBoundexception.

=========================================================

There are 2 keywords as throw and throws
throw is for throwing the new exception and throws is for when we knows that it can throw the exception so, it becme complsory to handle the error

we can say
class A {
    public void show() throws Exception{
            // code
    }

    the responsiblity of handling the exception is on the parent like from where it is called
    there in parent class surround the call with the try catch

}